1
00:00:02,954 --> 00:00:05,584
What is real freedom, 
what is liberation,

2
00:00:05,584 --> 00:00:09,017
what is that,
the spiritual inquiry

3
00:00:09,130 --> 00:00:13,321
beyond the base necessities 
of existence?

4
00:00:13,331 --> 00:00:15,812
That’s actually the hallmark
of spiritual culture.

5
00:00:15,812 --> 00:00:18,483
[Steppenwolf | Animal; Royal Edition]

6
00:00:18,843 --> 00:00:21,516
So Vedanta says, 
athāto brahma jijñāsā

7
00:00:21,527 --> 00:00:27,488
athāto—now that you’ve achieved
human life, inquire about brāhmaṇ.

8
00:00:27,488 --> 00:00:31,594
That’s where it begins,
that’s why it starts with word ‘now’.

9
00:00:31,595 --> 00:00:34,316
Some commentators explained, 
“It means,

10
00:00:34,316 --> 00:00:40,027
yes, now that you’ve achieved human life,
this is what it’s meant for.”

11
00:00:40,146 --> 00:00:45,521
What did Socrates say,
whom we mentioned earlier?

12
00:00:46,151 --> 00:00:52,875
“The unexamined life 
is not a life worth living.”

13
00:00:53,035 --> 00:00:59,382
That’s Socrates’s opinion,
expressed so long ago,

14
00:00:59,556 --> 00:01:02,260
thousands years ago.

15
00:01:02,260 --> 00:01:07,944
“An unexamined life
is not a life worth living.”

16
00:01:08,237 --> 00:01:12,896
Meaning ‘ātma-samīkṣa’,
self-analysis—

17
00:01:12,896 --> 00:01:15,511
to try and understand 
who I am,

18
00:01:15,511 --> 00:01:19,561
where have I come from,
what is my purpose.

19
00:01:20,631 --> 00:01:23,254
And they say,
“Well, what if someone

20
00:01:23,257 --> 00:01:26,089
is not interested in who they are, 
where they’ve come from,

21
00:01:26,089 --> 00:01:28,418
what their purpose is, 
but they are just basically

22
00:01:28,418 --> 00:01:32,911
interested in reproduction 
and family maintenance?”

23
00:01:35,071 --> 00:01:38,476
Hm … Okay … 
[Laughing]

24
00:01:40,664 --> 00:01:43,906
You mean like an animal?

25
00:01:45,236 --> 00:01:51,014
Who doesn’t … 
who has no capacity for self-inquiry,

26
00:01:51,014 --> 00:01:55,720
can reproduce 
and maintain their family.

27
00:01:56,680 --> 00:02:00,543
So Prabhupād said in one place 
about human beings in kali-yuga,

28
00:02:00,543 --> 00:02:04,787
“Man is a royal edition 
of the animal.”

29
00:02:11,781 --> 00:02:16,751
And there is one famous artist 
in the 20th century, he used to …

30
00:02:16,751 --> 00:02:19,571
You’ve probably seen these pictures 
somewhere on the network,

31
00:02:19,571 --> 00:02:22,287
like dogs playing poker.

32
00:02:24,771 --> 00:02:29,850
They’re all dogs in suits, 
smoking cigars, playing cards.

33
00:02:32,944 --> 00:02:37,250
I am not the first person
to make these observations.

34
00:02:37,250 --> 00:02:45,572
And it’s not just, “Oh, a bunch 
of fanatical people of this opinion.”

35
00:02:45,572 --> 00:02:50,099
Read “Steppenwolf”
by Hermann Hesse.

36
00:02:51,982 --> 00:02:57,494
The Steppenwolf, Harry Haller, 
goes to attend a lecture

37
00:02:57,607 --> 00:03:00,243
and everyone is there, and 
they are very impressed with the man.

38
00:03:00,243 --> 00:03:04,129
I forget if he even 
mentions what the subject is.

39
00:03:04,581 --> 00:03:07,914
And the host, who is writing 
about the Steppenwolf,

40
00:03:07,914 --> 00:03:10,588
he says, the lecturer said,

41
00:03:10,588 --> 00:03:13,105
maybe he’s talking 
about the Universe, the stars …

42
00:03:13,105 --> 00:03:16,054
whatever it was, 
it doesn’t even matter.

43
00:03:16,054 --> 00:03:21,454
It was the 19th century …
Whatever the latest theory was.

44
00:03:21,454 --> 00:03:25,435
And he said, 
“The Steppenwolf shot me a look,

45
00:03:25,443 --> 00:03:28,289
turned, looked at me.”

46
00:03:28,289 --> 00:03:31,352
And he said, 
“And in that look he”,

47
00:03:31,352 --> 00:03:33,675
I am paraphrasing now,

48
00:03:33,675 --> 00:03:37,799
“annihilated all 
of modern civilization.

49
00:03:37,799 --> 00:03:38,854
And it said to me,

50
00:03:38,854 --> 00:03:43,664
‘Look at what monkeys 
we’ve become.’”

51
00:03:43,963 --> 00:03:48,043
Written by Hermann Hesse 
a 100 years ago.

52
00:03:52,010 --> 00:03:54,160
Solzhenitsyn,

53
00:03:54,168 --> 00:03:58,161
“Serene voluntary self-restraint.”

54
00:03:58,161 --> 00:04:00,798
He said, 
“You have the freedom …”

55
00:04:00,798 --> 00:04:02,478
When he came to America,

56
00:04:02,478 --> 00:04:05,819
and they invited him to give 
the Harvard address to the students,

57
00:04:05,819 --> 00:04:10,910
and they thought, “Oh, now
Alexander, Sasha, will tell everyone

58
00:04:10,910 --> 00:04:14,562
how wonderful the United States is.”
And he said,

59
00:04:14,562 --> 00:04:18,172
“Well, I could never recommend 
what’s going on in the Soviet Union,

60
00:04:18,182 --> 00:04:19,870
what you’ve got 
going on here

61
00:04:19,870 --> 00:04:23,873
is less than something
for the dignity of man.”

62
00:04:23,892 --> 00:04:27,774
And he said, “You have the right 
to express anything and everything,

63
00:04:27,774 --> 00:04:30,052
but you’ve given up the right

64
00:04:30,052 --> 00:04:35,776
NOT to have your mind and soul
stuffed with nonsense,

65
00:04:35,776 --> 00:04:44,309
with gossip, with mundane, 
useless trivia, and information.

66
00:04:44,309 --> 00:04:45,829
That you’ve given up

67
00:04:45,829 --> 00:04:50,365
in the name of freely expressing 
anything and everything.”

68
00:04:54,435 --> 00:04:59,969
So, many have made

69
00:04:59,969 --> 00:05:03,251
(what they called his address, 
“A world split apart”)

70
00:05:03,251 --> 00:05:07,212
a scathing indictment 
of Western civilization.

71
00:05:07,288 --> 00:05:08,645
What did Gandhi say, 
when they said,

72
00:05:08,645 --> 00:05:11,788
“Mahatmaji, what do you think 
about Western civilization?”

73
00:05:11,788 --> 00:05:16,190
He said, 
“I think it would be a good idea.”

74
00:05:16,190 --> 00:05:18,310
[Laughing]

75
00:05:18,310 --> 00:05:23,837
How does Dostoevsky begin
“Notes From the Underground”?

76
00:05:25,237 --> 00:05:29,033
“I am an ugly man. 
I am an unhappy man.

77
00:05:29,033 --> 00:05:31,991
I am a sick man.”

78
00:05:36,292 --> 00:05:39,502
That’s the state of affairs.

79
00:05:40,062 --> 00:05:43,391
Why is he appreciated? 
For his honesty.

80
00:05:43,956 --> 00:05:47,596
What does he say?
“I would wonder how it is—

81
00:05:47,596 --> 00:05:51,176
I could in one moment 
be raising a glass,

82
00:05:51,176 --> 00:05:54,186
a toast to the Truth, 
the highest,

83
00:05:54,186 --> 00:05:57,394
the best, the spiritual,

84
00:05:57,804 --> 00:06:05,655
and in the next moment capable 
of sinking into the lowest slime.”

85
00:06:05,954 --> 00:06:08,573
He’s an honest man.

86
00:06:08,573 --> 00:06:13,912
Telling the situation, 
not trying to hide it.

87
00:06:15,800 --> 00:06:19,870
You have to call a spade a spade.

88
00:06:24,286 --> 00:06:27,531
And I know, you’re going,
“What does that mean?”

89
00:06:27,551 --> 00:06:29,806
[Laughing]

90
00:06:29,906 --> 00:06:33,751
Means being naked truth, 
be honest.

91
00:06:33,751 --> 00:06:37,358
We’re told, don’t speak
a truth that’s unpalatable.

92
00:06:38,414 --> 00:06:41,933
I have a problem with that
from time to time.

93
00:06:43,412 --> 00:06:47,205
But sometimes they say, 
“Sadhu means one,

94
00:06:47,205 --> 00:06:51,518
who cuts sharply
with unpleasant language.”

95
00:06:51,518 --> 00:06:53,952
The doctor, 
who removes the cancer

96
00:06:53,952 --> 00:07:00,376
does it with a scalpel.
Is he cruel?

97
00:07:00,376 --> 00:07:05,092
Or is he your real friend?
He’s removing the cancer.

98
00:07:05,092 --> 00:07:08,836
And this is how you do it.

99
00:07:09,466 --> 00:07:11,772
If somebody can do it 
in a sweet way,

100
00:07:11,772 --> 00:07:15,864
with the least amount of pain—
all the better.

